Verify Replication
# Create a test script to verify replication
cat > verify_cluster.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash

echo "=== Cluster Verification ==="
echo ""

echo "1. Checking ZooKeeper..."
if netstat -tuln | grep -q 2181; then
    echo "   [OK] ZooKeeper is running on port 2181"
else
    echo "   [FAIL] ZooKeeper is not running"
fi

echo ""
echo "2. Checking Kafka Brokers..."
for port in 9092 9093 9094; do
    if netstat -tuln | grep -q $port; then
        echo "   [OK] Broker on port $port is running"
    else
        echo "   [FAIL] Broker on port $port is not running"
    fi
done

echo ""
echo "3. Listing Topics..."
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/kafka-topics.sh --list --bootstrap-server localhost:9092

echo ""
echo "4. Topic Details..."
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/kafka-topics.sh --describe --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --topic test-cluster-topic

echo ""
echo "=== Verification Complete ==="
EOF

chmod +x verify_cluster.sh
./verify_cluster.sh
Expected Results
ZooKeeper running on port 2181
Three Kafka brokers running on ports 9092, 9093, 9094
Topic test-cluster-topic exists with 3 partitions
Each partition has 3 replicas distributed across brokers
All replicas are in-sync (ISR count = 3)
Messages can be produced and consumed successfully
Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: Broker Fails to Start
# Check logs
tail -f /opt/kafka/logs/server.log

# Common causes:
# - Port already in use
# - Insufficient memory
# - ZooKeeper not running
Issue: Cannot Connect to Broker
# Verify broker is listening
netstat -tuln | grep 9092

# Check firewall rules
sudo ufw status

# Test connection
telnet localhost 9092
Issue: Out of Sync Replicas
# Check under-replicated partitions
$KAFKA_HOME/bin/kafka-topics.sh --describe \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --under-replicated-partitions

# Restart affected broker
Cleanup Commands
# Stop all Kafka brokers
pkill -f 'kafka.Kafka'

# Stop ZooKeeper
pkill -f 'org.apache.zookeeper'

# Remove data directories (optional - for fresh start)
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/kafka-logs-*
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/zookeeper
Conclusion
You have successfully:

Installed Apache Kafka and ZooKeeper on a Linux machine
Configured a 3-broker Kafka cluster on a single node
Created replicated topics with multiple partitions
Tested message production and consumption
Verified cluster resilience by simulating broker failure
Monitored cluster health and partition distribution
Key Takeaways:

Kafka clusters provide fault tolerance through replication
ZooKeeper coordinates broker metadata and leader election
Multiple brokers can run on a single machine using different ports
Replication factor determines data redundancy
Partitions enable parallel processing and scalability
